postcontent: Maybe I need to rewrite my add. Yes, I'm aware the gun new is $325 or so, depending on where you buy it. I gave $340 for mine because I'm in a small town. It would have cost me more in gas than I would have saved. These guns aren't hand crafted. They are put together assembly line style, and sometimes you don't get a great trigger like I like. If I buy a gun to keep, I have it tweaked to MY standards, as in this case. I had a trigger job done on it, they honed the original seers instead of throwing in some crap off eBay. I had the feed ramp polished, a tighter hammer to keep down misfires, and lightened the recoil on it so it could have a bullet racked in just by using the rear sight and my boot one handed. title: For Sale:  1951 Russian built SKS Rifle
postcontent: Manufactured in Russia at the Tula Arsenal in 1951. The rifle was factory refurbished at some point and all parts have matching serial numbers. Visually the weapon is in excellent condition and mechanically it is about as close to factory new as possible. Notice I did not say "original" because if I needed a screw, I would simply upgrade to stainless steel and not worry because it was not the "original" part. There are no critical component reproductions used in the rifle because none of them have ever failed and show little to no sign of wear. After every use I disassemble the rifle completely, clean, lube and inspect all parts. I even remove the firing pin and polish it, but not for looks. This is not an SKS for the collector but the one that is to be used and depended on when needed. Comes with the original sling and Strip Clip Ammo Belt. I also have several 30 round magazines, a couple of 10 round and probably 50 or more 10 round strip clips used to load the original factory 10 round magazine. The bayonet, cleaning rod and around 250 rounds of ammo are included. Unfortunately, I lost the cleaning kit that came with the weapon, but fortunately I have one of my own which does a far better job for my needs.
